        "title_en": "The Infrastructure War: SpaceX, Fusion, and Space Data Centers",
        "title_pl": "Wojna infrastruktury: SpaceX, fuzja i kosmiczne centra danych",
        "body_en": "While model makers competed on benchmarks, the real battle shifted to infrastructure. Reflection AI signed a $6.3 billion deal with SpaceX for the Colossus 2 data center — at $150 million per month through 2029, with access to NVIDIA GB300 chips. This puts Anthropic and Reflection AI side by side as SpaceX's anchor compute tenants.\n\nOn the Diamandis podcast, the conversation extended beyond Earth. StarCloud CEO Philip Johnson revealed that the first NVIDIA H100 GPU reached orbit in November 2025 aboard a Falcon 9, and the first LLM was trained in space. The pitch is compelling: unlimited solar power, no cooling needed, no NIMBY protests. Space-based data centers are being positioned as the natural evolution of compute infrastructure.\n\nMeanwhile, Helion — backed by Sam Altman — cleared Washington state regulatory approvals for its Orion Fusion power plant, expected to deliver 400MW. Peter Diamandis declared: \"If you were watching the right metric, you could predict when this is going to happen and it's imminent.\" Nuclear fusion is moving from \"always 50 years away\" to a concrete timeline.\n\nBack on Earth, Groq raised $650 million in its pivot from chipmaker to inference-focused cloud, and Baseten secured $1.5 billion for AI inference infrastructure. Subquadratic, a Miami startup, demonstrated 12 million token context windows at 50x the speed of FlashAttention and 20x cheaper.\n\nThe Orin Token Price Index told the story in numbers: token prices have dropped approximately 1000x in a few years. Intelligence is becoming a commodity, and the infrastructure players are positioning for a world where compute is the new oil.",
